<font color="#FF0000">THE RICE PADDIES IN SEPTEMBER</font><br>
<tt>Sun Sep 14 18:58:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Art:<br>
Well said, I hope somebody is writing all this down. I really hear what you've said. Perhaps some day History will reflect what truly transpired, Something real and honest and not the half-truths found in the Pentagon Papers.<br><br>
As far as civilians working on our bases, I had heard of the Barber on Hill 37 as being a possible VC, a month ago I met the Marine that shot him as he stormed the hill with a group of Sappers. <br>
Sometimes the individual you met while on patrol you weren't too sure if you weresuppose  to salute him, reach out and shake his hand or kill him.  As M24 said, &quot;Damned if you do and damned if you don't!&quot;<br><br>
M24, <br>
My Captain has been fighting cancer now for some time, he said something that really meant a lot to all of us at the reunion. He said:<br>
&quot;Often, when I was feeling all that pain, I realized that it was just another rice paddy I had to cross. When I really needed help, I wrapped all of you guys, all of the Marines in India Company all around me and got through another night.&quot; <br><br>
Unlike you, September of 1967 was a quite month for us, the Special Forces camp at Thung Duc got overrun again and of course we responded. June, July, November and May were the worst months for me. I don't like May, it was in May that I lost it and came back at the same time. It was in May that I awoke from a deep sleep and from wondering in a never land of truth, shadows and the past. It was in May that I realized I was that old timer on the back of the six-by truck and the kids replacing me were too young to understand.<br>
 What hurt, was that I could not take what was in my mind and heart and give to them. That experience they would have to learn on their own.  They would have to lose their innocence on their own.  I was there for some guys; I could not be there for others. <br><br>
M24, Thanks for being there and here, Many more would thank you for being there in September. We couldn't all be where we thought we should have been. That, &quot;If Only,&quot; can play havoc with our minds. <br><br>
Sorry, I meant to say I'll send you my mug with the m-60 and the Elvis sideburns. I figured I knew you well enough to include my M-60 in the picture, that way at night before you go to sleep you can say, &quot;Good night Cook Barela, where ever you are.&quot;<br><br>
The book is still being edited but I will send you a copy before submission, I value your opinion before publication. Meanwhile, I will be glad to read yours, your poems have been a tremendous point of reference and reflection and because they were written by you, I've have had to read them over slowly (not because of the big words), but because of the true spirit of Vietnam they have captured.<br><br>
Til then, keep your clothes and helmet on, and watch your back door.<br>
 <br>

<p><code>-- Just another Rice Paddy, we have to cross  (Sparrowhawk, In Peace and War) </code><p>


